<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Theology and Spirituality in Modern Scottish Land Reform</title></head><body><div><h1 style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Alastair McIntosh BSc MBA PhD, Fellow of the Centre for Human Ecology, Govan, on psychological and spiritual benefits of land reform</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">I was a founder and leader of the original Isle of </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Eigg</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Trust that raised £1.6 million and bought </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Eigg</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> into Community ownership in 1997, setting a template for subsequent community buyouts. I am also currently, or have been until recently, the Visiting Professor of Human Ecology at the University of Strathclyde, an Honorary Fellow at Edinburgh University’s School of Divinity, and a Senior Honorary Research Fellow at the University of Glasgow. My work on land, community and environment is best expressed in my book </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Soil and Soul</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Aurum</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">, London, 2001), described by George </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Monbiot</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> as “world-changing” and by Bishop James Jones as “life-changing”. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">I am confining my testimony to one simple observation that ties in with points 1, 2 and 4 of the Committee’s remit. In this I simply want to state what may be so obvious that it slips through unsaid in the more specialised testimonies that the committee will receive. In my experience, the greatest benefit, and the prime driver of land reform in modern Scotland, is the psychological and spiritual empowerment that precedes the wider socio-economic and environmental benefits. In a nutshell:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Community land tenure empowers the people because it re-grounds their capacity, dignity and confidence, opening up access to life’s most basic resource and drawing them from disempowerment to empowerment; towards lives more richly abundant. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">My supporting basis for maintaining this is laid out in the paper which was published in a leading international journal jointly with my former student, </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Rutger</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Henneman</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">, who carried out the field work under my partial supervision with the </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Law and Governance Group at </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Wageningen</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> University.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">That italicised statement, above, is all that I need to say. It drives what I have elsewhere</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> called the Cycle of Belonging, by which, a) a Sense of Place engenders, b) a Sense of Identity, informing, c) a Sense of Values and from that, motivating d) the Sense of Responsibility that drives change and reconstitutes a damaged Sense of Place. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 10.3pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">The Political Theology of Modern Scottish Land Reform</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">Published by The Journal for the Study of Nature, Religion and Culture, University of Florida, Vol. 3:3, 2009, pp. 340-375</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> Alastair McIntosh, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Rekindling Community: Connecting People, Environment and Spirituality</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">, Schumacher Briefings No 15, Green Books, Totnes, published in association with WWF International.</span></p></body></html>